          "body": "The Philistines regroup and raid the valley again (v. 13). This recurrence is a test: will David repeat the previous strategy without asking? He does not. 'David inquired again of God' (v. 14). The divine answer this time is categorically different: do not go directly; circle behind; wait for the sound of marching in the balsam tree tops. The balsam trees (or mulberry trees, *bakah*) were apparently well-known to the combatants in the valley. God appoints a supernatural sound in their canopy as the battle-signal — most commentators understand this as the movement of angelic forces preceding the Israelite advance (cf. 2 Kings 6:17; Ps. 68:17). The sound in the trees was God going out before the army. David's obedience is certified in the Chronicler's exact phrase: 'David did just as God had commanded him' (v. 16). The result is the most comprehensive territorial sweep of the chapter — from Gibeon to Gezer, the entire Philistine corridor in the Shephelah is cleared. Eugene Merrill (Kingdom of Priests, Baker Academic, 1987) notes that this victory effectively ended the Philistine threat in the highlands for the duration of David's reign. The lesson the Chronicler encodes is methodological: the habit of inquiry must be renewed for each new situation — prior success is not a template for present obedience."
