          "body": "The chapter's final verse is its theological summit. 'Then the fame of David went out into all the lands; and the LORD brought the fear of him on all the nations.' Both verbs belong to the LORD: it is the LORD who spreads the fame and the LORD who plants the dread. David is the object of these divine actions, not their agent. The word for fame is *shem* — the same word used for the names of David's Jerusalem-born sons in verse 4. The Chronicler has quietly bookended the chapter: names given to children in Jerusalem (v. 4) become a name known among the nations (v. 17). The word for fear (*pachad*) is the heavy term for dread, the terror that immobilizes. This language echoes the Exodus narrative — the same dread fell on Canaan's nations when they heard of Israel's Red Sea crossing (Exod. 15:14-16) and when Israel crossed the Jordan (Josh. 2:9-11). David's victories are thus framed within the larger narrative of God's unfolding plan for Israel and the nations — a plan in which the Davidic kingdom is not the end but a stage, pointing beyond itself to the coming Davidic king before whom every nation will ultimately tremble."
