        "excerpt": "And David realized that the LORD had established him as king over Israel, and that his kingdom was highly exalted, for the sake of His people Israel.",
        "body": "The opening two verses establish the chapter's theological grammar. Hiram's embassy is a political event that David reads as a theological text. The word *yada* — to know, to perceive, to have experiential recognition — marks a moment of insight rather than mere information. David is not told that God has established him; he perceives it from the evidence of a Gentile king's deference. This is the Chronicler's recurring epistemological claim: the faithful king reads Providence.\n\nThe verb *kun* (established, fixed) is the load-bearing word. In the Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7:12-16, God promises to 'establish' (*kun*) David's throne, David's son's kingdom, and the Davidic line. When the Chronicler uses this verb here, he is signaling that 1 Chronicles 14 is a narrative illustration of covenant-fulfillment. The cedar logs from Tyre are not merely building materials; they are evidence that the covenant is being kept.\n\nThe phrase 'for the sake of His people Israel' is the Chronicler's most important corrective to Davidic triumphalism. The kingdom is not established for David's glory. It is established for Israel — and Israel exists for the nations (Gen. 12:1-3). The Chronicler's post-exilic audience, stripped of throne and temple, needed to hear that God's purposes for His people were not undone. The kingdom was God's project from the beginning; even its apparent collapse in 586 BC did not terminate the divine intention.\n\nThe Reformed tradition rightly emphasizes that this recognition of divine establishment is itself a gift — it takes Spirit-illumined eyes to read Providence correctly (Calvin, *Institutes* 1.17.1-2). Unregenerate rulers accumulate the same evidence and call it their own achievement. David's recognition is a mark of genuine covenant relationship, not unusual personal modesty.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yada* (realized/knew) — experiential, relational knowledge, not mere cognitive awareness. *Kun* (established) — the Davidic covenant verb, 2 Sam. 7:12, 13, 16; 1 Chron. 17:11, 12, 14. *Nasa* (exalted) — literally 'lifted up'; combined with *maal* (upward), the expression is intensely vertical — God did the lifting."
