        "title": "The household in Jerusalem — blessing as concrete, not abstract (14:3-7)",
        "range": "14:3-7",
        "excerpt": "Then David took more wives at Jerusalem, and David became the father of more sons and daughters.",
        "body": "The genealogical register of verses 3-7 is not historical filler. The Chronicler consistently uses genealogical material to carry theological argument — the entire opening nine chapters of 1 Chronicles demonstrate this. Here, the register documents the materialization of blessing in David's Jerusalem household. Deuteronomy 28:4 promises that covenant faithfulness produces fruitful offspring; the thirteen names of vv. 4-7 are that promise made concrete.\n\nThe Chronicler's note that David 'took more wives' (v. 3) has generated significant discussion. He records the fact without editorial comment, unlike the Deuteronomic law's explicit prohibition against the king multiplying wives (Deut. 17:17). The Chronicler is not endorsing polygamy; he is narrating the growth of the Davidic house as part of the blessing-demonstration. The sins of David that the Samuel narrative records in detail — Bathsheba, Uriah, the census — the Chronicler largely omits, not from dishonesty but from purpose: he is painting the ideal portrait, the model of inquiry and obedience, for his post-exilic audience. The omissions are hermeneutical, not deceptive.\n\nThe name Solomon (v. 4) in the Jerusalem birth-list deserves special attention. The Chronicler places Solomon in the list without fanfare, but his entire subsequent narrative (1 Chron. 22 – 2 Chron. 9) will pivot on Solomon as the temple-builder. The seed is planted here, in a list of children, before Solomon has spoken a word. God's purposes are embedded in ordinary household events long before they become visible to history.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ben* (sons) and *bat* (daughters) — both are tokens of divine blessing in the covenant vocabulary of Deuteronomy 28. *Shem* (names, v. 4) — the same word used in v. 17 for David's fame; the Chronicler's wordplay is deliberate."
